.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.WITH" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.with \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.with()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]with()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing this date\-time
with some fields replaced by new values.
Because all \f[CR]Temporal\f[R] objects are designed to be immutable,
this method essentially functions as the setter for the date\-time\(cqs
fields.
.PP
To replace the \f[CR]calendarId\f[R] property, use the
\f[CR]withCalendar()\f[R] method.
To replace the \f[CR]timeZoneId\f[R] property, use the
\f[CR]withTimeZone()\f[R] method.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
with(info)
with(info, options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]info\f[R]
An object containing at least one of the properties recognized by
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from()\f[R] (except \f[CR]calendar\f[R] and
\f[CR]timeZone\f[R]): \f[CR]day\f[R], \f[CR]era\f[R] and
\f[CR]eraYear\f[R], \f[CR]hour\f[R], \f[CR]microsecond\f[R],
\f[CR]millisecond\f[R], \f[CR]minute\f[R], \f[CR]month\f[R],
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R], \f[CR]nanosecond\f[R], \f[CR]offset\f[R],
\f[CR]second\f[R], \f[CR]year\f[R].
Unspecified properties use the values from the original date\-time.
You only need to provide one of \f[CR]month\f[R] or
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R], and one of \f[CR]era\f[R] and \f[CR]eraYear\f[R]
or \f[CR]year\f[R], and the other will be updated accordingly.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
An object containing some or all of the following properties (in the
order they are retrieved and validated):
.RS
.TP
\f[B]disambiguation\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
What to do if the local date\-time is ambiguous in the given time zone
(there are more than one instants with such local time, or the local
time does not exist).
Possible values are \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqearlier\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqlater\(dq\f[R], and
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqcompatible\(dq\f[R].
For more information about these values, see ambiguity and gaps from
local time to UTC time.
.TP
\f[B]offset\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
What to do if the offset is explicitly provided in \f[CR]info\f[R] but
the offset is invalid for the given time zone in the given local time.
Possible values are \f[CR]\(dquse\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqignore\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R], and \f[CR]\(dqprefer\(dq\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqprefer\(dq\f[R].
For more information about these values, see offset ambiguity.
.TP
\f[B]overflow\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying the behavior when a date component is out of range
(when using the object \f[CR]info\f[R]).
Possible values are:
.RS
.TP
\f[B]\(dqconstrain\(dq\f[R] (default)
The date component is clamped to the valid range.
.TP
\f[B]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R]
A \f[CR]RangeError\f[R] is thrown if the date component is out of range.
.RE
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object, where the fields
specified in \f[CR]info\f[R] that are not \f[CR]undefined\f[R] are
replaced by the corresponding values, and the rest of the fields are
copied from the original date\-time.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]info\f[R] is not an object.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]options\f[R] is not an object or \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.RE
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The provided properties that specify the same component are
inconsistent.
.IP \(bu 2
The provided non\-numerical properties are not valid; for example, if
\f[CR]monthCode\f[R] is never a valid month code in this calendar.
.IP \(bu 2
The provided numerical properties are out of range, and
\f[CR]options.overflow\f[R] is set to \f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The wall\-clock time represented by the provided properties is ambiguous
in the time zone, and \f[CR]options.disambiguation\f[R] is set to
\f[CR]\(dqreject\(dq\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The result is not in the representable range, which is ±10\(ha8 days, or
about ±273,972.6 years, from the Unix epoch.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using with()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] newZDT = zdt.with({ hour: 13 });
console.log(newZDT.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-07\-01T13:34:56\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples, see the documentation for the individual properties
that can be set using \f[CR]with()\f[R].
.SS Offset during date changes
By default, the \f[CR]offset\f[R] option is set to
\f[CR]\(dqprefer\(dq\f[R], which means we use the original offset (or
that provided in \f[CR]info\f[R]) if it\(cqs valid, and recalculate
otherwise.
This means if you set to another date that has a different offset due to
a DST transition, the offset will be recalculated:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] newZDT = zdt.with({ month: 12 });
\f[I]// The offset is recalculated to \-05:00\f[R]
console.log(newZDT.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-12\-01T12:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
And if you set the time to within the DST transition, the offset is used
to resolve the ambiguity:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-02T01:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] newZDT = zdt.with({ day: 3 });
console.log(newZDT.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] zdt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-04T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] newZDT2 = zdt2.with({ day: 3 });
console.log(newZDT2.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:05:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
If you use \f[CR]offset: \(dquse\(dq\f[R], then the offset will be used
as\-is to obtain the exact time first, and \f[I]then\f[R] recalculate
the offset:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
\f[B]const\f[R] newZDT = zdt.with({ month: 12 }, { offset: \(dquse\(dq });
\f[I]// The offset is recalculated to \-05:00, but the wall\-clock time changes\f[R]
console.log(newZDT.toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2021\-12\-01T11:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
You can also set \f[CR]offset: \(dqreject\(dq\f[R] to throw an error if
the original offset is invalid, forcing an explicit new offset to be
specified:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] zdt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
zdt.with({ month: 12 }, { offset: \(dqreject\(dq });
\f[I]// RangeError: date\-time can\(aqt be represented in the given time zone\f[R]
zdt.with({ month: 12, offset: \(dq\-05:00\(dq }, { offset: \(dqreject\(dq }).toString();
\f[I]// \(dq2021\-12\-01T12:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
